                                <date>1958</date>. С. <biblScope unit="page">??–??</biblScope>.</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><xi:include href="../encodingdesc.xml" parse="xml"/></teiHeader><text><body><entry xml:id="entry_adæm" xml:lang="os"><form type="lemma"><orth>adæm</orth></form><sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>люди</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>people</q></abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>народ</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>nation</q></abv:tr></sense></sense><abv:exampleGrp><abv:example><quote>adæmy farn bīræ ū</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>фарн народа велик</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>the %ifarn%i [abundance, blessing] of the people is great</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_ЮОПам."/><biblScope>III 189, ср. %sКоста%s 39</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example><quote>adæmæn sæ ræsūǧd wættæ qarmæj, rajʒastæj læwwync</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>у людей красивые комнаты стоят теплые, светлые</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>people's beautiful rooms are [lit. stand] warm, filled with light</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Коста"/><biblScope>25</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example><quote>iron adæm</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>осетинский народ</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>Ossetian nation</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Брит."/><biblScope>100</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example><quote>æmæ jæ fædyl cydīs bīræ adæm</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>и следовало за ним множество народа</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>a lot of people followed him</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Матфей"/><biblScope>%i4%i 25</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example><quote>adæm tærxon kænyn rajdydtoj</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>народ стал судить</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>the people started to judge</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Сека"/><biblScope>18</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example><quote>adæm fæsabyr sty</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>народ затих</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>the peopled calmed down</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Сека"/><biblScope>17</biblScope></bibl></abv:example><abv:example xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg><lang/></usg><quote>sæ astæw adæmtæ bacudæj</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>между ними вошли (посредниками) люди</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>between them came people (as intermediaries)</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_LQ"/><biblScope>III 38</biblScope></bibl></abv:example></abv:exampleGrp><etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang="ar" extralang="fa trk"><lang/> <w>ādam</w> <gloss><q>человек</q></gloss></mentioned>. Слово распространено по всему Кавказу: <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>adamiani</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w>adamili</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/> <w>adamina</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ʽadam</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"><w>ʽadan</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="ce" extralang="inh"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar" extralang="krc-x-karachay"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned>. Ср. также: <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/> <w>ādam</w></mentioned> (<bibl><author>Залеман</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ИАН"/><biblScope>1907, стр. 537</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="yai"><lang/> <w>ādam</w> <gloss><q>человек</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="yai"><w/> <gloss><q>люди</q></gloss></mentioned>. В осетинском неоформленное %iadæm%i имеет значение не индивида, а коллектива: ‘люди’, ‘народ’, и уже отсюда, с помощью суффикса %i-ag%i, образовано понятие ‘человек’; аналогичную картину мы находим в племенных названиях: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætær"/> ‘татары’ — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætæjrag"/> ‘татарин’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒy"/> ‘грузины’ — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒiag"/> ‘грузин’, и т. п.; объясняется это, несомненно, тем, что в осознании людей той эпохи, которую отражает в данном случае осетинский язык, понятие коллектива было первичным, а понятие индивида — вторичным.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>9. — </biblScope></bibl><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>119.</biblScope></bibl></etym><etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="ar" extralang="fa trk"><lang/> <w>ādam</w> <gloss><q>person, human being</q></gloss></mentioned>. The word is widespread all across the Caucasus: <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>adamiani</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w>adamini</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/> <w>adamina</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ʽadam</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"><w>ʽadan</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="inh" extralang="ce"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar" extralang="krc-x-karachay"><lang/> <w>adam</w></mentioned>. Compare <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/> <w>ādam</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Залеман._Ягн."/><biblScope>IAN 1907, p. 537</biblScope></bibl>) <mentioned xml:lang="yai"><lang/> <w>ādam</w> <gloss><q>person, people</q></gloss></mentioned>. In Ossetic %iadæm%i without suffixation refers not to an individual, but to a group: ‘people’, ‘nation’. The word for ‘person’ is derived from this root using the suffix %i-ag%i. A similar situation is observed for tribal or national names: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætær"/> ‘the Tatars’ — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætæjrag"/> ‘a Tatar’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒ"/> ‘the Georgians’ — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒiag"/> ‘a Georgian’, etc. The explanation for this is surely that in the conscience of the people of earlier times, reflected here in the Ossetic language, the concept of a group was primary, and the concept of an individual was secondary.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>9.</biblScope></bibl> — <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>119.</biblScope></bibl></etym></entry></body></text></TEI>